nner"><div class=3D"wpb_wrapper">
	<div class=3D"wpb_text_column wpb_content_element">
		<div class=3D"wpb_wrapper">
			<p>At Dressel Divers, we know that the difference between psi and bar ca=
n be disconcerting when trying to measure tank pressure. For that reason, w=
e offer scuba gear adapted to both psi and bar measurements. In this way, o=
ur guests know they will be able to interpret the measurements without maki=
ng calculations. However, knowing the difference between psi and bar can be=
 useful in case you travel to other destinations or dive with other diving =
centers less adapted to your needs. Let=E2=80=99s see it!</p>
<h2><strong>The Difference Between Psi And Bar</strong></h2>
<p>Psi and bar are both pressure measurements. For instance, when we look a=
t the pressure gauge, we see a measure of the tank filling pressure. As we =
know, pressure is the amount of force applied per unit of area.&nbsp; The m=
ost common measurements we find are psi or pounds per square inch (lb/in2) =
and bar or kilograms per square centimeter (Kg/cm2). The <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_units">imperial system</a>, from the Anglo-=
Saxon countries, uses psi, and the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Metric_system">metric system</a> uses bar.</p>

		</div>
